ref> || Best Actress || Kristen Stewart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Film Critics Association]] || Best Actress || Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[List of film awards|International Cinephile Society]]\n|Best Picture\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{draw|3rd place}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Original Screenplay\n|Olivier Assayas|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Film Editing\n|[[Marion Monnier]]|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[List of film awards|Talk Film Society]]\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[The Village Voice|Village Voice Annual Film Poll]]\n|Best Film\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{draw|7th place}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{draw|5th place}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[List of film awards|Fright Meter Awards]]\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Costume Design\n|[[J\u00fcrgen|J\u00fcrgen Doering]]|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Screenplay\n|Olivier Assayas|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Sant Jordi Awards]]\n|Best Foreign Film\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Actress in a Foreign Film\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb title|4714782}}\n* {{Rotten Tomatoes|Personal_Shopper}}\n* {{metacritic film|personal-shopper}}\n*[https://www.criterion.com/current/posts/5067-personal-shopper-freedom-2016 ''Personal Shopper: Freedom 2016''] an essay by Glenn Kenny at the [[Criterion Collection]]\n\n{{Olivier Assayas}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Personal Shopper}}\n[[Category:2010s ghost films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:2010s thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:2016 films]]\n[[Category:Belgian films]]\n[[Category:Belgian mystery films]]\n[[Category:Belgian thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Czech drama films]]\n[[Category:Czech films]]\n[[Category:Czech mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:English-language French films]]\n[[Category:Films about fashion]]\n[[Category:Films about twins]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:Films set in Oman]]\n[[Category:Films set in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Oman]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Paris]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Prague]]\n[[Category:Films with screenplays by Olivier Assayas]]\n[[Category:French films]]\n[[Category:French-language films]]\n[[Category:French mystery drama films]]\n[[Category:French mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:French psychological drama films]]\n[[Category:French psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:French thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:German films]]\n[[Category:German mystery thriller films]]\n[[Category:German psychological thriller films]]\n[[Category:German thriller drama films]]\n[[Category:Haunted house films]]\n[[Category:Supernatural drama films]]\n[[Category:2010s supernatural thriller films]]\n[[Category:Swedish-language films]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|2016 film}}\n{{for|the occupation|Personal shopper}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Personal Shopper\n| image          = Personal Shopper poster.jpg\n| caption        = Theatrical release poster\n| director       = [[Olivier Assayas]]\n| producer       = [[Charles Gillibert]]\n| writer         = Olivier Assayas\n| starring       = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Kristen Stewart]]\n* [[Lars Eidinger]]\n* Sigrid Bouaziz\n* [[Anders Danielsen Lie]]\n* Ty Olwin\n* Hammou Graia\n* Nora von Waldstatten\n* [[Benjamin Biolay]]\n* Audrey Bonnet\n* [[Pascal Rambert]]<!--DO NOT CHANGE based upon poster billing-->\n}}\n| music          = \n| cinematography = [[Yorick Le Saux]]\n| editing        = [[Marion Monnier]]\n| studio         = {{Plainlist|\n* CG Cin\u00e9ma\n* Vortex Sutra\n* Detailfilm\n* Sirena Film\n* [[Arte France Cin\u00e9ma]]\n* Arte Deutschland/WDR\n* [[Canal+]]\n* [[Cin\u00e9+]]\n}}\n| distributor    = {{plainlist|\n* The Searchers (Belgium)\n* Artcam Films (Czech Republic)\n* [[Les Films du Losange]] (France)\n* Weltkino Filmverleih (Germany)\n}}\n| released       = {{Film date|2016|5|17|[[2016 Cannes Film Festival|Cannes]]|2016|12|14|Belgium and France|2017|1|19|Germany|2017|4|27|Czech Republic|df=yes}}\n| runtime        = 106 minutes\n| country        = {{Plainlist|\n* France\n* Germany\n* Czech Republic\n* Belgium\n}}\n| language       = {{Plainlist|\n* English\n* French\n* Swedish\n}}\n| budget         = $1 million \n| gross          = $2.7 million<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.the-numbers.com/movie/Personal-Shopper-(France)#tab=summary|title=Personal Shopper|website=[[The Numbers (website)|The Numbers]]|accessdate=15 January 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''''Personal Shopper''''' is a 2016 [[Supernatural fiction|supernatural]] [[psychological thriller]] film written and directed by [[Olivier Assayas]].<ref name=\"nytimes\">{{cite news|last=Scott|first=A. O.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/09/movies/personal-shopper-review-kristen-stewart.html|title=Review: Kristen Stewart Is Entrancing as a Haunted 'Personal Shopper'|work=The New York Times|date=9 March 2017|accessdate=10 November 2017}}</ref> The film stars [[Kristen Stewart]] as a young American woman in Paris who works as a personal shopper for a celebrity and tries to communicate with her deceased twin brother.\n\nAn [[international co-production]] between Belgium, Czech Republic, France and Germany,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.moma.org/calendar/events/3699 |title=''Personal Shopper''. 2016. Directed by Olivier Assayas |publisher=[[Museum of Modern Art]] |accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> the film was selected to compete for the [[Palme d'Or]] at the [[2016 Cannes Film Festival]].<ref name=IW>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/cannes-live-stream-2016-film-festival-lineup-list|title=2016 Cannes Film Festival Announces Lineup|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=IndieWire}}</ref><ref name=Var>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/festivals/cannes-film-festival-official-selection-lineup-2016-1201753269/|title=Cannes 2016: Film Festival Unveils Official Selection Lineup|accessdate=14 April 2016|work=Variety}}</ref> At Cannes, Assayas shared the [[Best Director Award (Cannes Film Festival)|Best Director Award]] with [[Cristian Mungiu]], who directed ''[[Graduation (2016 film)|Graduation]]''.<ref name=\"Director\">{{cite web|url=https://deadline.com/2016/05/cannes-film-festival-winners-2016-palme-dor-ful-list-1201760956/|title=Cannes Film Festival Winners: Palme d'Or to Ken Loach's 'I, Daniel Blake'|accessdate=22 May 2016|work=Deadline}}</ref> The film was released on 14 December 2016 in France and 10 March 2017 in the United States. The film received positive reviews from critics, with particular praise for Stewart's performance.\n\n==Plot==\nMaureen is a personal shopper in Paris for Kyra, a demanding supermodel. Her twin brother Lewis recently died from a heart condition, a condition shared by Maureen. They were both interested in [[spiritualism]] and felt they were mediums.\n\nMaureen stays overnight at her late brother's home, hoping for a sign from him, and has a brief encounter with a spiritual presence. His girlfriend Lara wants to sell the mansion to a couple who knew and loved her brother, but they want Maureen to find out if the mansion has spirits, benevolent or malevolent. Maureen and her brother had promised each other that who ever died first would give the other a sign after death. During her discussion with the potential buyers, Maureen discovers the artist [[Hilma af Klint]], whose paintings were inspired by messages from the spirit world. Maureen video chats with her boyfriend Gary, who is on a contract job in [[Oman]] and encourages her to get away from Paris and Kyra and to come visit. He tells her there is nothing after death.\n\nAt Kyra's apartment, Maureen meets and talks with Kyra's lover Ingo, who tells her Kyra is planning to break up with him because she is afraid her husband will discover their relationship. Maureen spends another night at Lewis' home and the faucets turn on. She asks Lewis to talk with her, and discovers that her artwork has been scratched out. She is terrified by an aggressive, angry specter of a woman. Maureen flees the house.\n\nOn her way to London to pick up clothing for Kyra, Maureen receives a series of text messages from an unknown number, which she suspects is her late brother Lewis. The sender toys with Maureen, and encourages her to try on Kyra's clothes, which she has been forbidden to do. She spends the night in Kyra's bed, in a dress collected from London. The female spectre appears in the bedroom whilst Maureen sleeps for a few seconds, causing Maureen to wake up suddenly. The next morning, Maureen visits Lara to tell her that there is no longer a supernatural presence in the mansion. The sender also leaves her a room key for a hotel. When she visits the room in one of Kyra's dresses, no one is there, but when she checks at the front desk, she discovers the room is booked in her name and has been pre-paid in cash.\n\nAfter picking up expensive jewelry for Kyra, Maureen returns to Kyra's apartment, where she discovers Kyra's bloody corpse, and sees fleeting images. She is questioned by the police, who ask about the location of the jewelry. Later, Maureen discovers the jewelry is in her apartment. The unknown texter demands she return to the hotel room, which she does, with the jewelry.\n\nDoors in the hotel open and close, although no one is seen going through them. Ingo leaves the hotel, and is apprehended by two men. He shoots one and attempts to escape. However, he is arrested and confesses to murdering Kyra.\n\nMaureen meets Lara's new boyfriend Erwin, who was friends with Lewis before his death. They speak about the possibility that Lewis's soul is still present. As Maureen sits in the garden, a wind stirs, and a glass behind her levitates and falls to the floor.\n\nMaureen flies to Oman to visit Gary in the mountains. Arriving at his room, she hears a noise and finds a glass floating in the air; it falls and shatters. She asks questions, accepting single thumps as yes, two for no. When she eventually asks her twice-repeated question, \"Lewis, is it you,\" there is silence. She then asks, \"Or is it just me?\" A single thump for yes.\n\n==Cast==\n* [[Kristen Stewart]] as Maureen Cartwright\n* [[Lars Eidinger]] as Ingo\n* [[Nora Waldst\u00e4tten]] as Kyra Gellman\n* [[Anders Danielsen Lie]] as Erwin\n* Sigrid Bouaziz as Lara\n* Ty Olwin as Gary\n* Audrey Bonnet as Cassandre\n* [[Pascal Rambert]] as Jerome\n* Hammou Graia as Police Officer\n* [[Benjamin Biolay]] as [[Victor Hugo]]\n\n==Production==\nIn May 2015, it was announced that [[Olivier Assayas]] would be directing the film, from a screenplay he wrote, with [[Kristen Stewart]] starring. He wrote it for Stewart as the star, as he had worked with her in ''[[Clouds of Sils Maria]]''. [[Charles Gillibert]] produced the film under his CG Cinema banner.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/kristen-stewart-ghost-story-shopper-olivier-assayas-1201497322/|title=Cannes: Kristen Stewart to Star in Ghost Story \u2018Personal Shopper\u2019 for Olivier Assayas (EXCLUSIVE)|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=15 May 2015|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> In October 2015, Sigrid Bouaziz, [[Lars Eidinger]], Anders Danielsen Lie, and Nora von Waldst\u00e4tten also had been cast in the film.<ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://www.screendaily.com/news/assayas-stewart-reuniteon-set-ofpersonal-shopper/5095473.article|title=Olivier Assayas, Kristen Stewart reunite on set of 'Personal Shopper'|website=Screen Daily|first=Melanie|last=Goodfellow|date=14 October 2015|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> In November 2015, Ty Olwin joined the cast, taking the role of Gary, Maureen's boyfriend.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.reelchicago.com/article/olwin-lands-first-role-costarring-assayas-feature151123|title=Olwin lands first film role in an international feature|website=ReelChicago.com|first=Ruth L|last=Ratney|date=23 November 2015|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>\n\nPrincipal photography began on 27 October 2015 in Paris, France for two weeks and then moved to Prague, London, and Oman.<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\n==Release==\nThe film had its world premiere at the [[Cannes Film Festival]] on 17 May 2016, where it competed for the [[Palme d'Or]].<ref name=IW/><ref name=Var/> The film was distributed by Les Films du Losange in France, and [[IFC Films]] in North America.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/berlin-kristen-stewarts-shopper-tops-mk2-sales-deals-1201705532/|title=Berlin: Kristen Stewart\u2019s \u2018Shopper\u2019 Tops MK2 Sales Deals|publisher=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Elsa|last=Keslassy|date=13 February 2016|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref> [[Universal Pictures]] distributed the film internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/global/universal-kristen-stewart-personal-shopper-1201789244/|title=Universal Picks Up Kristen Stewart\u2019s \u2018Personal Shopper\u2019 in Multiple Territories|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Leo|last=Barraclough|date=6 June 2016|accessdate=5 August 2016}}</ref> The film was screened at the [[2016 Toronto International Film Festival]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tiff.net/films/personal-shopper/|title=Personal Shopper|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref> and the [[New York Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmlinc.org/nyff2016/films/personal-shopper/|title=Personal Shopper - NYFF54|publisher=|accessdate=6 October 2016}}</ref>\n\nIt was released in France on 14 December 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmsdulosange.fr/en/film/228/personal-shopper|title=Personal Shopper|website=[[Les Films du Losange]]|accessdate=2 April 2017}}</ref> The film was released in the United States on 10 March 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/hollywood/2016/09/kristen-stewart-personal-shopper-trailer|title=Kristen Stewart Just Can\u2019t Give Up the Ghost in Personal Shopper|website=[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]|first=Hillary|last=Busis|date=29 September 2016|accessdate=29 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn the United States, the movie grossed $79,175 on 4 theaters for an average of $19,794, the highest of the weekend, after adding 31 theaters the next weekend it saw a 92.6% increase to gross $152,478. The movies final US domestic total was $1,305,195 and a worldwide gross of $2.2 million against a $1 million budget, it was a box office success.\n\n==Critical reception==\n''Personal Shopper'' received generally positive reviews from film critics. ''[[The Guardian]]'' awarded the film five stars, calling it \"uncategorisable yet undeniably terrifying\".<ref name=\"Guardian\">{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/may/16/personal-shopper-review-kristen-stewarts-psychic-spooker-is-a-must-have|title=Personal Shopper review: Kristen Stewart's psychic spooker is a must-have|access-date=17 May 2016|work=The Guardian}}</ref> [[Stephanie Zacharek]] of ''[[Time (magazine)|Time]]'' gave a positive review, writing that \"''Personal Shopper'' is a strange and beautifully made film, and both star and director are clearly energized by their dual mission.\" She also listed it as one of ''Time'''s top ten films of 2017.<ref>{{cite web|last=Zacharek|first=Stephanie|authorlink=Stephanie Zacharek|url=http://time.com/5045566/top-10-movies-2017/|title=The Top 10 Movies of 2017|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=7 December 2017|accessdate=13 December 2017}}</ref> [[A. O. Scott]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' wrote the film is \"sleek and spooky, seductive and suspenseful. It flirts with silliness, as ghost stories do. And also with heartbreak.\"<ref name=\"nytimes\"/>\n\n[[Rotten Tomatoes]] reports a \"Certified Fresh\" score of 80% based on 261 reviews with an average rating of 7.13/10. The site's critical consensus reads, \"''Personal Shopper'' attempts a tricky series of potentially jarring tonal shifts with varying results, bolstered by a performance from Kristen Stewart that's impossible to ignore.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/personal_shopper/|title=Personal Shopper (2016)|website=[[Rotten Tomatoes]]|access-date=15 January 2019}}</ref> On [[Metacritic]], the film holds a rating of 77 out of 100, based on 38 critics, indicating \"generally favorable reviews\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/movie/personal-shopper/details|title=Personal Shopper|website=Metacritic|access-date=15 January 2019}}</ref> The film was booed at its initial screening at the Cannes Film Festival, about which director Assayas said, \"It happens every {{sic|once and a while}} where people just don't get the ending.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/kristen-stewart-booed-cannes-personal-shopper-1201776099/|title=Kristen Stewart\u2019s \u2018Personal Shopper\u2019 Booed at Cannes Premiere|publisher=Variety|first=Variety|last=Staff|date=16 May 2016|access-date=21 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/05/17/kristen-stewarts-film-boo-ed-cannes/84480184/|title=Why was Kristen Stewart's 'Personal Shopper' booed at Cannes?|website=[[USA Today]]|first=Bryan|last=Alexander|date=17 May 2016|access-date=21 May 2016}}</ref> At its official premiere at Cannes, the film received a 4 1/2-minute standing ovation.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/article/kristen-stewart-personal-shopper-standing-ovation-after-boos-20160518|title=Kristen Stewart's 'Personal Shopper' Receives Standing Ovation At Cannes Premiere After Getting Booed|first=Liz|last=Calvario|date=18 May 2016|access-date=21 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/kristen-stewarts-personal-shopper-receives-895145|title=Cannes: Kristen Stewart's 'Personal Shopper' Receives 4-Minute-Plus Standing Ovation|first=Chris|last=Gardner|date=17 May 2016|access-date=21 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width: 99%;\"\n|-\n! Year !! Organization !! Category !! Recipient(s) and Nominee(s) !! Outcome\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2016 || [[Cannes Film Festival]] || Best Director || [[Olivier Assayas]] || {{win}}\n|-\n|[[Oaxaca FilmFest]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thekrisworld.canalblog.com/archives/2016/10/16/34446024.html|title=Personal Shopper: Prix de la meilleure actrice \u00e0 l'Oaxaca Film Festival|access-date=14 November 2016|date=16 October 2016}}</ref> || Best Actress || [[Kristen Stewart]] || {{win}}\n|-\n|[[Online Film Critics Society]]\n|Best Non-U.S. Release\n|''Personal Shopper''\n|{{Won}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"10\" |2017\n|[[Austin Film Critics Association]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ATXFilmCritics/status/947204146234642432|title=Austin Film Critics on Twitter|publisher=}}</ref> || Best Actress|| Kristen Stewart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[Dublin Film Critics' Circle]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.ie/cinema/news/Dublin-Film-Critics-Circle-Awards-for-2017-announced/400171.htm|title=Dublin Film Critics Circle Awards for 2017 announced|first=|last=Entertainment.ie|publisher=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> || Best Actress|| Kristen Stewart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[Florida Film Critics Circle]]\n|Best Cinematography\n|[[Yorick Le Saux]]|| {{Nominated}}\n|- \n|[[List of film awards|Indiana Film Journalists Association]] <ref>{{cite web|url=http://indianafilmjournalists.com|title=Indiana Film Journalists Association|website=indianafilmjournalists.com|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> || Best Actress || Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[Indiewire|Indiewire Annual Critics Poll]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.indiewire.com/2017/12/best-movies-2017-critics-films-performances-get-out-phantom-thread-lady-bird-1201909032/2/|title=2017 Critics Poll: The Best Films and Performances According to Over 200 Critics|first=Eric|last=Kohn|date=19 December 2017|publisher=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref>\n|Best Film\n|''Personal Shopper''\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| Best Actress || Kristen Stewart || {{draw|5th place}}\n|-\n|[[List of film awards|International Cinephile Society]]\n|Best Picture Not Released in 2016\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[International Film Festival Rotterdam]]\n|Best Director\n|Olivier Assayas\n|{{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[List of film awards|Las Vegas Film Critics Society]] <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/wordsbycbiggs/status/941476558316773377/photo/1?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw&ref_url=http://www.kstewfrance.com/2017/12/personal-shopper-kristen-nominee-dans_16.html|title=Alright, ballot is due for the .@LVFilmCritics. Find out what wins at the #LVFCSAwards on Dec. 18th!pic.twitter.com/SzgEo7N5yf|first=Colin|last=Biggs|publisher=|accessdate=21 December 2017}}</ref> || Best Actress || Kristen Stewart || {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| [[St. Louis Film Critics Association]] || Best Actress || Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"12\" |2018\n| rowspan=\"4\" |[[List of film awards|International Cinephile Society]]\n|Best Picture\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{draw|3rd place}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Original Screenplay\n|Olivier Assayas|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Film Editing\n|[[Marion Monnier]]|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|[[List of film awards|Talk Film Society]]\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |[[The Village Voice|Village Voice Annual Film Poll]]\n|Best Film\n|''Personal Shopper''|| {{draw|7th place}}\n|-\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{draw|5th place}}\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |[[List of film awards|Fright Meter Awards]]\n|Best Actress\n|Kristen Stewart|| {{Nominated}}\n|-\n|Best Costume Design\n|[[