               = 182\n| total goals                     = 476\n| league topscorer           = [[Bernd Bauchspie\u00df]] (18)<ref>''fuwo'', page: 93</ref>\n| attendance                    = 1,785,000<ref name=\"Fuwo\" >''fuwo'', page: 23</ref>\n| average attendance      = 9,808<ref name=\"Fuwo\" />\n| prevseason                 = [[1958 DDR-Oberliga|1958]]\n| nextseason                 = [[1960 DDR-Oberliga|1960]]\n}}\nThe '''1959 DDR-Oberliga''' was the eleventh season of the [[DDR-Oberliga]], the first tier of [[East German football league system|league football]] in [[East Germany]]. Rather than in the traditional autumn-spring format the Oberliga played for six seasons from 1955 to 1960 in the calendar year format, modelled on the system used in the [[Soviet Union]]. From 1961\u201362 onwards the league returned to its traditional format.\n\nThe league was contested by fourteen teams. [[FC Erzgebirge Aue|SC Wismut Karl-Marx-Stadt]], incidentally based at [[Aue]] and not [[Chemnitz|Karl-Marx-Stadt]], won the championship, the club's last of three national East German championships.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrchamp.html |title= East Germany - List of Champions |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref name=\"Meister\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.dfb.de/historie/ddr-fussball/meister/ |title= DDR-Meister |date= |website=dfb.de |publisher=[[German Football Association]] |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=German|trans-title= East German champions}}</ref> On the strength of the 1959 title Wismut qualified for the [[1960\u201361 European Cup]] where the club was knocked out by [[SK Rapid Wien]] in the first round. League runners-up [[FC Viktoria Frankfurt|ASK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin]] qualified for the [[1960\u201361 European Cup Winners' Cup]] instead of [[FDGB-Pokal]] winner [[SC Dynamo Berlin]] and was knocked out by [[Rud\u00e1 Hv\u011bzda Brno]] in the preliminary round.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec196061.html |title= European Competitions 1960-61|date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref>\n\n[[Bernd Bauchspie\u00df]] of [[Chemie Zeitz]] was the league's top scorer with 18 goals.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/torschuetzenkoenige/gdr-oberliga/ |title= DDDR \u00bb Oberliga \u00bb Torsch\u00fctzenk\u00f6nige  |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga top scorers }}</ref>\n\n==Table==\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\t\nThe 1959 season saw two newly promoted clubs, [[Lok Stendal|BSG Lokomotive Stendal]] and [[Chemie Zeitz]].<ref name=\"Ddr\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesd/ddrhist.html |title= East Germany 1946-1990 |date= |website= rsssf.com |publisher= |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=|trans-title=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.weltfussball.de/spielplan/gdr-oberliga-1959-spieltag/26/ |title= DDR \u00bb Oberliga 1959 |date= |website= Weltfussball.de |publisher= |access-date= 19 January 2016|language=German|trans-title=DDR-Oberliga 1959}}</ref>\t\n{{fb cl header|sort=y|winpoints=2}}\n|-style=\"background:#ddffdd\"\n||1||[[FC Erzgebirge Aue|SC Wismut Karl-Marx-Stadt]]||26||17||5||4||44||25||+19||39\n|-style=\"background:#bbccff;\"\n||2||[[FC Viktoria Frankfurt|ASK Vorw\u00e4rts Berlin]]||26||13||9||4||49||24||+25||35\n|-style=\"background:#E6E6FA;\"\n||3||[[SC Dynamo Berlin]]||26||14||5||7||46||26||+20||33\n|-\n||4||[[F.C. Hansa Rostock|SC Empor Rostock]]||26||10||9||7||36||26||+10||29\n|-\n||5||[[FC Carl Zeiss Jena|SC Motor Jena]]||26||10||9||7||29||27||+2||29\n|-\n||6||[[Fortschritt Wei\u00dfenfels]]||26||10||7||9||36||39||-3||27\n|-\n||7||[[SC Aktivist Brieske-Senftenberg]]||26||8||8||10||36||30||+6||24\n|-\n||8||[[FSV Zwickau|BSG Motor Zwickau]]||26||9||6||11||30||32||-2||24\n|-\n||9||[[FC Sachsen Leipzig|SC Lokomotive Leipzig]]||26||8||8||10||28||36||-8||24\n|-\n||1