{"title_page": "Schism of Montaner", "text_new": "{{short description|Conversion of an Italian village to the Orthodox church}}\n[[File:Montaner - Chiesa cattolica - Foto di Paolo Steffan.jpg|thumb|250px|The Catholic church of Montaner, dedicated to [[Pancras of Rome|Saint Pancras]]]]\n \nIn the '''Schism  of Montaner''' between 1967 and 1969, almost all residents of the Italian village of {{ill|Montaner (Sarmede)|it|lt=Montaner}} renounced [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]] and embraced the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]. This was due to a disagreement with the bishop of [[Diocese of Vittorio Veneto|Vittorio Veneto]], Albino Luciani, the future [[Pope]] [[John Paul I]], over the appointment of the local priest.\n\n== Background ==\nMontaner is a [[frazione]] in the municipality of [[Sarmede]] in the [[Province of Treviso]], Italy. On December 13, 1966, Giuseppe Fa\u00e8, the [[parish]] [[priest]], died.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=246|oclc=607552761}}</ref> Fa\u00e8, who had served the community for forty years, had proven popular with the people of Montaner.<ref name=\":0\" /> He aided in the obtaining electricity and running water for the village, the construction of a new school, and even aided in the organization of anti-fascist resistance to the [[Operation Achse|German Occupation]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=246-247|oclc=607552761}}</ref> After his death, the bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Vittorio Veneto|Vittorio Veneto]] decided to appoint Giovanni Gava as the new priest, which was unpopular among the villagers. They instead supported Antonio Botteon, who, for a long time, had assisted the old priest.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=247|oclc=607552761}}</ref> As a last resort, Botteon was asked to become the vice-rector of the parish.\n\nOn January 21st, 1967, the new priest arrived in town, however, the night before his arrival, the townspeople erected a wall blocking the entrance of the church, and a mob of townspeople prevented him from carrying out his work.<ref name=\":1\" />\n \nLuciani replied that for a village as small as Montaner, one priest was enough, while noting that priests are not elected by the people but appointed by their bishop. The bishop appointed a former Franciscan as a temporary rector, Father Casimiro from [[Monselice]], again failing to meet the citizens' requests.\n\nLuciani's final decision was to appoint a new rector, Pietro Varnier. But on September 12, 1967, disgruntled citizens locked Varnier in the attic of the rectory. Luciani then arrived in Montaner, escorted by police, and removed the [[Blessed Sacrament]] from the Church, leaving the Church unblessed.\n\n== The schism ==\n[[File:Montaner - Chiesa ortodossa - Foto di Paolo Steffan.jpg|thumb|280px|The Orthodox Church of Montaner]]\nThe people then founded the Orthodox Church of Montaner. On December 26, 1967, the first [[Divine Liturgy]] was celebrated with the Orthodox Byzantine rite. The Orthodox priest, Claudio Vettorazzo, was permanently installed in June 1969 and on September 7, 1969, the Orthodox church was blessed. Residents of the village recall that the initial time period after the schism resulted in \"hatred\" and \"confusion\" within the village.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=250-251|oclc=607552761}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Vettorazzo was imprisoned because of legal and financial problems.<ref>[http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/agosto/05/sesso_droga_casa_del_vescovo_co_0_9408058135.shtml Sexe et drogue dans la maison de l'''\u00e9v\u00eaque'']</ref>\n \nOnly after 1998 was the Orthodox Church of Montaner officially recognized by the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Patriarchate of Constantinople]], to use the [[Byzantine Rite]]. In 2000, a nunnery associated with the church was founded. \n\nToday, the Catholic and Orthodox communities still exist within the village, though divisions remain.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Orthodox parish is also frequented by immigrants from [[Eastern Europe]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Schism]]\n*[[Old and New Light]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  Valentina Ciciliot, ''Il caso Montaner. Un conflitto politico tra chiesa cattolica e chiesa ortodossa'', Venezia - Ca' Foscari, 2004. {{in lang|it}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l_9FV9jE6N8 The schisme of Montaner in Youtube] {{in lang|it}}\n* [http://montaner.sarmede.free.fr/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=56 Reportage of TV  RAI about Montaner] {{in lang|it}}\n\n[[Category:Schisms from the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy in Italy]]\n[[Category:Veneto]]\n[[Category:1960s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1967 in Christianity]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Conversion of an Italian village to the Orthodox church}}\n[[File:Montaner - Chiesa cattolica - Foto di Paolo Steffan.jpg|thumb|250px|The Catholic church of Montaner, dedicated to [[Pancras of Rome|Saint Pancras]]]]\n \nIn the '''Schism  of Montaner''' between 1967 and 1969, almost all residents of the Italian village of {{ill|Montaner (Sarmede)|it|lt=Montaner}} renounced [[Catholic Church|Catholicism]] and embraced the [[Eastern Orthodox Church]]. This was due to a disagreement with the bishop of [[Diocese of Vittorio Veneto|Vittorio Veneto]], Albino Luciani, the future [[Pope]] [[John Paul I]], over the appointment of the local priest.\n\n== Background ==\nMontaner is a [[frazione]] in the municipality of [[Sarmede]] in the [[Province of Treviso]], Italy. On December 13, 1966, Giuseppe Fa\u00e8, the [[parish]] [[priest]], died.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=246|oclc=607552761}}</ref> Fa\u00e8, who had served the community for fourty years, had proven popular with the people of Montaner.<ref name=\":0\" /> He aided in the obtaining electricity and running water for the village, the construction of a new school, and even aided in the organization of anti-fascist resistance to the [[Operation Achse|German Occupation]].<ref>{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=246-247|oclc=607552761}}</ref> After his death, the bishop of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Vittorio Veneto|Vittorio Veneto]] decided to appoint Giovanni Gava as the new priest, which was unpopular among the villagers. They instead supported Antonio Botteon, who, for a long time, had assisted the old priest.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=247|oclc=607552761}}</ref> As a last resort, Botteon was asked to become the vice-rector of the parish.\n\nOn January 21st, 1967, the new priest arrived in town, however, the night before his arrival, the townspeople erected a wall blocking the entrance of the church, and a mob of townspeople prevented him from carrying out his work.<ref name=\":1\" />\n \nLuciani replied that for a village as small as Montaner, one priest was enough, while noting that priests are not elected by the people but appointed by their bishop. The bishop appointed a former Franciscan as a temporary rector, Father Casimiro from [[Monselice]], again failing to meet the citizens' requests.\n\nLuciani's final decision was to appoint a new rector, Pietro Varnier. But on September 12, 1967, disgruntled citizens locked Varnier in the attic of the rectory. Luciani then arrived in Montaner, escorted by police, and removed the [[Blessed Sacrament]] from the Church, leaving the Church unblessed.\n\n== The schism ==\n[[File:Montaner - Chiesa ortodossa - Foto di Paolo Steffan.jpg|thumb|280px|The Orthodox Church of Montaner]]\nThe people then founded the Orthodox Church of Montaner. On December 26, 1967, the first [[Divine Liturgy]] was celebrated with the Orthodox Byzantine rite. The Orthodox priest, Claudio Vettorazzo, was permanently installed in June 1969 and on September 7, 1969, the Orthodox church was blessed. Residents of the village recall that the initial time period after the schism resulted in \"hatred\" and \"confusion\" within the village.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite book|last=|first=|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/607552761|title=Conversion in the age of pluralism|date=2009|publisher=Brill|others=Giordan, Giuseppe.|year=|isbn=978-90-474-4494-7|location=Leiden|pages=250-251|oclc=607552761}}</ref>\n\nIn 1994, Vettorazzo was imprisoned because of legal and financial problems.<ref>[http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/agosto/05/sesso_droga_casa_del_vescovo_co_0_9408058135.shtml Sexe et drogue dans la maison de l'''\u00e9v\u00eaque'']</ref>\n \nOnly after 1998 was the Orthodox Church of Montaner officially recognized by the [[Ecumenical Patriarchate of Constantinople|Patriarchate of Constantinople]], to use the [[Byzantine Rite]]. In 2000, a nunnery associated with the church was founded. \n\nToday, the Catholic and Orthodox communities still exist within the village, though divisions remain.<ref name=\":2\" /> The Orthodox parish is also frequented by immigrants from [[Eastern Europe]].\n\n==See also==\n*[[Schism]]\n*[[Old and New Light]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*  Valentina Ciciliot, ''Il caso Montaner. Un conflitto politico tra chiesa cattolica e chiesa ortodossa'', Venezia - Ca' Foscari, 2004. {{in lang|it}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=l_9FV9jE6N8 The schisme of Montaner in Youtube] {{in lang|it}}\n* [http://montaner.sarmede.free.fr/modules.php?name=News&file=article&sid=56 Reportage of TV  RAI about Montaner] {{in lang|it}}\n\n[[Category:Schisms from the Catholic Church]]\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodoxy in Italy]]\n[[Category:Veneto]]\n[[Category:1960s in Italy]]\n[[Category:1967 in Christianity]]\n", "name_user": "Vanisaac", "label": "safe", "comment": "Correcting spelling: fourty->forty", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Schism_of_Montaner"}
{"title_page": "Olavi Ouvinen", "text_new": "{{short description|Finnish boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Olavi Ouvinen\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Finnish\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1926|12|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vyborg|Viipuri]], Finland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1990|2|6|1926|12|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Helsinki, Finland\n}}\n\n'''Olavi Ouvinen''' (10 December 1926 &ndash; 6 February 1990) was a Finnish [[boxing|boxer]].  <ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.fightsrec.com/olavi-ouvinen.html|title=Olavi Ouvinen boxer|website=www.fightsrec.com|access-date=2020-04-17}}</ref>He competed in the [[Boxing at the 1948 Summer Olympics \u2013 Bantamweight|men's bantamweight]] event at the [[1948 Summer Olympics]].<ref name=\"SportsRef\">{{cite Sports-Reference |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/olympics/athletes/ou/olavi-ouvinen-1.html |title=Olavi Ouvinen Olympic Results |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouvinen, Olavi}}\n[[Category:1926 births]]\n[[Category:1990 deaths]]\n[[Category:Finnish male boxers]]\n[[Category:Olympic boxers of Finland]]\n[[Category:Boxers at the 1948 Summer Olympics]]\n[[Category:People from Vyborg]]\n{{Finland-boxing-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Finnish boxer}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox sportsperson\n| name           = Olavi Ouvinen\n| full_name      = \n| image          = \n| caption        = \n| nationality    = Finnish\n| sport          = [[Boxing]]\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1926|12|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place    = [[Vyborg|Viipuri]], Finland\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1990|2|6|1926|12|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place    = Helsinki, Finland\n}}\n\n'''Olavi Ouvinen''' (10 December 1926 &ndash; 6 February 1990) was a Finnish [[boxing|boxer]